                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d358">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/13887: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Algiers</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cole</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Algiers</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-12T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 12, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>399. Personal for the Under Secretary from Murphy. Your 234, August 6, 10 p.m.
                    General Weygand was pleased and encouraged to receive the contents of your
                    message under reference which I conveyed to him this morning. He had just given
                    me the information reported in my 398, August 12, 3 p.m., to the effect that the
                    Vichy meeting had not resulted in concession to the Germans regarding French
                    Africa. Apropos of your message he said with a smile that “I hope this does not
                    mean that you plan to attack us,” and [apparent omission] [“]I’ll be happy to
                    receive any data you may be in position to send.[”]</p>
                <p>Repeated to Vichy. [Murphy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cole</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
